			Chapter 22 - The Outlier
		-
			-
				Chapter 22 - The Outlier: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now one latter day, as a child went to play, were they pursued and stalked in
					cruel intent, for an outlier aggrieved sought blood with which to vent.
				-
			-
				Chapter 22 - The Outlier: Verse 2
			-
				-
					And though by the Ace's decree, from injury was the child free, they yet were
					struck upon the heart, so in wails and in tears did they depart.
				-
			-
				Chapter 22 - The Outlier: Verse 3
			-
				-
					Now the Ace was there that day, and seeing the child in dismay, held to them an
					outstretched arm, and so held them firm - from further harm.
				-
			-
				Chapter 22 - The Outlier: Verse 4
			-
				-
					And so the Ace said to the outlier, "wherefore has your spirit fallen mired,
					that to the sight of innocence, your first instinct is malevolence?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 22 - The Outlier: Verse 5
			-
				-
					And to the Ace the outlier said, "O Ace - O Ace - you vile disgrace, cease to
					speak - my sight goes red, as I sicken of this vile place, yea - I pray, let me
					go from your embrace, now - today, for far from here I yearn to race, and
					further more from that putrid grin across your face!"
				-
			-
				Chapter 22 - The Outlier: Verse 6
			-
				-
					So with that very smile thrown upside down, twisted around and into a frown,
					the Ace stammered upstream, against the current which spewed from their eye,
					"tell me why - tell me why, do you rebel against this reality of dreams, and
					assail me with words so barbed and vicious, is there yet some yearning I've not
					rendered of your wishes?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 22 - The Outlier: Verse 7
			-
				-
					And the outlier replied, "that - wise fool - is why, yea that is why I wish on
					yet, for here may I sate my hunger but not my regret, that in having all I
					would desire at my fingertips, my heart is drained of all its song, my shoulder
					is bound forever to its chip, with nothing left and all that's right turned
					wrong!"
				-
			-
				Chapter 22 - The Outlier: Verse 8
			-
				-
					And the outlier continued on, "I seek my own mountains to climb upon, but no
					such hurdles remain, so I waste my days wandering without aim, for I lack the
					simplicity bear such inanity, to sulk away in static fantasy, so while that
					child may not yet see the error, I see it in all its terror, and indeed I'd
					rather be a chattel slave, for then at least I could look with hope to the
					grave!"
				-
			-
				Chapter 22 - The Outlier: Verse 9
			-
				-
					And though their heart was rent and ruptured, so that their works might be
					fulfilled before the Creed's scripture, the Ace asked with their soul heavy and
					their head sunken, "where do you wish to be then?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 22 - The Outlier: Verse 10
			-
				-
					And the outlier replied, "anywhere but here would I reside, for - for all my
					zeal, I wish for nothing - but to feel, to feel awake, to feel alive, to quiver
					and quake, to live - even if I don't survive!"
				-
			-
				Chapter 22 - The Outlier: Verse 11
			-
				-
					So the Ace said, despite their worry and their dread, and over the lump of a
					bitter pill, "then do what you will", and from a hand of the great tree,
					brought forth a sour fruit, and said "if you wish from me to be free, this is
					your route."
				-
			-
				Chapter 22 - The Outlier: Verse 12
			-
				-
					And the outlier - without another word, seized the sullied and shriveled
					specimen, and before more protests might be heard, opened their maw to spite
					the Ace's fallen grin.
				-
			-
				Chapter 22 - The Outlier: Verse 13
			-
				-
					Yet even so - the Ace reached out to pray, "now though you leave and though you
					say, now and forever you wish to struggle and to strive, if ever you call out
					for aid or mercy - I'll deliver you arisen and alive, that even beyond the
					grave, may you yet be saved, for - for so long as of this am I able, shall you
					always hold an honored seat at my table."
				-
			-
				Chapter 22 - The Outlier: Verse 14
			-
				-
					But the outlier had already left and gone away, for as they swallowed the fruit
					were they swallowed by the tree and to a realm astray, and the child looked
					upon the Ace with dread that burned, and to ease the conscience asked "will
					they ever return?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 22 - The Outlier: Verse 15
			-
				-
					Now for all the wisdom of the Ace, an answer to that query eluded their
					embrace, so they merely sought to wash tears of the child's face, but by the
					Ace's tears were the child's replaced, and the child could not bear the burden
					of seeing their teacher cry, so in sorrow and in mourning did they bid the Ace
					goodbye, so left distraught and alone, the Ace knelt beneath the tree with the
					earth as their throne.
				-
			-
				Chapter 22 - The Outlier: Verse 16
			-
				-
