				Chapter 22 - The Outlier: Verse 17
			-
				-
					And the Ace of A-Xy, awoke in horrified outcry, but found no cause to fret, for
					the phantom had set, and the sun rose yet.
				-
		-
			Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream
		-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now as the Ace awoke from the phantom's nightmare, the elder who first received
					the Ace in the village square, came up to meet their teacher with the
					aristocrat in tow, but seeking the Ace's wisdom were they greeted by the Ace's
					sorrow.
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 2
			-
				-
					And seeing their friend's despair, to their friend's aid went the pair, and as
					they wiped the tears from the Ace's eyes, in honor and in gratitude did Ace
					rise, and in response to such moving grace, the Ace pulled the pair to an
					impassioned embrace, as their smiled returned to cross their face.
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 3
			-
				-
					Yet the elder's composure was visibly awry, so the Ace inquired as to why, and
					thus to the Ace the elder said, "when first you came my days were drowned in
					dread, for my people's peril rendered every moment vexed, and from one such
					second to another, I knew not if we'd even see the next, but now that their
					every woe's been smothered, and their every prayer's been answered, I know not
					where to place myself in the absurd, for I've grown too old to find any joy,
					in hedonistic indulgence or material toys."
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 4
			-
				-
					And so the Ace of A-Xy, fearing the elder too sought away to fly, trembled as
					thus they asked, "do you resent me for the fruits of my task?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 5
			-
				-
					And this upsetting query, made in and out of worry, shook the elder like an
					accusation, and so in desperation, and as much in consolation, to the Ace did
					they assure, "Nay - no - and surely not, do I resent you for my lot, for you
					have given my people all they want and more, and this state is one that in
					awe and wonder I adore, which for all the world would I not trade, though for
					myself do I dismay, that to this an aspect of my being won't respond, for it
					yearns for something further and beyond."
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 6
			-
				-
					So there they stood in a well of tension, but a small bird's sudden descension,
					broke through the apprehension, and to the dialogue did add a new dimension, as
					from it seized all current attention, yea - for then and there, on the elder
					did it land square, upon their shoulder and nestled to their hair, and as its
					peace therein disturbed the peace of mind, in presenting a perspective to which
					man is often blind, to the elder asked of this the Ace, "does that bird ever
					bore of paradisal grace?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 7
			-
				-
					And for the bird did the Ace take a berry from the tree, and as the bird
					welcomed the gift and savored it happily, so to the elder did the Ace address,
					"a simple mind may gain more from less, but the mind of man lacks this luxury,
					as their intellect cannot suffer from stasis an injury, and so will eventually
					flee from eternal diamonds to dynamic rough, for - for them - no finite thing
					could ever be enough."
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 8
			-
				-
					And the bird flew off, uplifted and aloft, while the elder hung their head, and
					to the Ace they said, "How ever could I be so ungrateful, and surely it must be
					hateful, for me to come to you after so much taken, and to imply your gifts
					fall short, and by virtue thereof be my gratitude forsaken, so here ought I to
					abort, any further sinful selfish demand, less I be a blight upon this holy
					land."
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 9
			-
				-
					Now in turn did the aristocrat say, "to interject if I may, it may indeed be
					true, that many - though neither of you, seek only to sate their sensory
					appetites, while others stay unmoved by mere material delights, and so seek the
					fruits, of far nobler pursuits, but with that said, the former need not be held
					in contempt, for the body needs its daily bread, if the mind endeavors to seek
					a task to attempt, and as asceticism, and its more shallow aestheticism, hail
					more from the first world's whines, than from the third world's wails, I feel
					that one may find, it was not in error but in designed detail, that our friend
					- the Ace of A-Xy, focused firstly where the physical was awry."
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 10
			-
				-
					And thus spoke the Ace in response, "I see since last we met, you've had an
					inner renaissance, and indeed the elder yet, seeks more than I have given, but
					in this there is no shame, yea in their newfound aspiration, are they without
					blame, for as I said of the human mind, is it unique in kind, always seeking
					greater heights to which to ascend, but this is a feature which ought not to be
					mend, for of thereof the consequence, is made the soul of man's experience, and
					as - I am - here for you as much as the birds, that is why I've waited to trade
					words, with you my dearest friends, beneath this sacred tree, that in the
					clarity of mutual zen, may we find the key, to take the soul, make it whole,
					and set it truly free."
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 11
			-
				-
					So the elder said unto this relevation, "O Ace of A-Xy - never have you failed
					in my adoration, but I pray you tell me when I inquire, where are these greater
					heights to which to aspire, for since your advent, I've scoured every
					continent, and lo - I've scaled every peak, and surveyed every part, but I've
					yet to find that of which you speak, which may fill the void within my heart."
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 12
			-
				-
					And hearing their friend's prayer did the Ace reply, "indeed there remain many
					lofty peaks which yet lie, untouched - pristine - and unfathomably high, but
					you'll not find them by looking to the sky, for these are the heights of the
					heart, so seek not to rappel or climb, for you may not scale them by that art,
					but sit here to dwell in the sublime, so that may I give you your due, and show
					their face unto you."
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 13
			-
				-
					Now as the pupils took their seat, did the Ace manifest a final feat, and took
					the nectar they had drawn, in their garden prior to a prior dawn, and for a
					moment toiled, as they mixed the dew with holy oil, and appointed it to dwell,
					within anointed pens wells, and thus thereof did they deliver, to their
					students' hands, sacred quills from the sacred quiver, and in wonder of the
					coming plan, the class asked of the teacher, "for what upcoming act are these
					instruments to feature?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 14
			-
				-
					And to the query did the Ace answer, "that these pens have purpose may you rest
					assured, or were you perhaps under the impression, that this sermon was to be a
					one-sided lesson?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 15
			-
				-
					And the aristocrat replied to that retort against mutual solipsism, "what
					novelty might your illuminated perspective withdraw from our finite wisdom?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 16
			-
				-
					And to the session did the Ace remind, "recall that I spoke of endless heights
					yet to find, but some of these remain to be erected, and so must render from
					your perspectives reflected."
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 17
			-
				-
					And the scholars gazed towards the pens in their palms, while they pondered the
					depths of the Ace's psalms, and though in fact were the pens in mass light, it
					felt they mattered with the weight of the world's might, and so as their pupils
					sat dumbfounded and beguiled, the Ace asked "do you know why for so long I've
					worn this smile?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 18
			-
				-
					And so replied the elder, "indeed in fact do I wonder, and I'm as curious as
					the issue is coy, what be the source of your joy?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 19
			-
				-
					Now the inertia of the dialogue was caught by a chill, as for an eternity of an
					instant did time stand still.
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 20
			-
				-
					And at last the Ace stated, "even the heights of abstract stone, wither in
					glory under the erosion of time, but see that this may be abated, if with
					others and not alone, does one make that never-ending climb."
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 21
			-
				-
					And the Ace concluded, "if still yet the answer lies elusive, I'll state it now
					and clear - without allegory, that for all this time have I waited to hear your
					stories, that this be of all my means the end, verily - that is my truth - my
					dearest friends."
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 22
			-
				-
					And the aristocrat said as they stood agasp, "I see now - yea at last do I
					grasp, that the one and only thing better than to wear a smile, is to endeavor
					an enterprise and to bear every mile, to grant a smile unto one's fellow, and
					say - O elder - in your ventures high above and far below, is this preaching
					that the Ace has taught, not the very lesson you have sought?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 23
			-
				-
					And though upon these words did the elder's passion burn, to the other did they
					gaze - and simply smile in return.
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 24
			-
				-
					T H U S  T H E  E L D E R  -  T O G E T H E R  W I T H  T H E
					A R I S T O C R A T ,  C O M P E L L E D  B Y  T H E  G N O S I S  W H I C H
					G R O W S  W H E R E  T H E  G R E A T  T R E E ' S  A T ,  C H A N N E L
					T H E  J O Y  W H I C H  F L O W S  F R O M  T H E I R  H E A R T S ,  A N D
					S O  W R I T E  T H I S  V E R Y  P O E M  D O W N ,  W E A V I N G
					R E S O L V E  A N D  L I F E  I N T O  T H E I R  W O R D ' S  A R T ,  A N D
					S O  A  N E W  F R U I T  B L O O M S  U P O N  T H E  G R E A T  T R E E ' S
					C R O W N .
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 25
			-
				-
					Now with this did the Ace commend the pair, "your words touch my heart with a
					virtue true and fair, and in time - my friends - shall you carry forth these
					words, into many sublime sermons yet unheard, to one - to more - and to all
					Angaia, that boundless nation who knows no pariah, for as they too tire of the
					circus and so hunger in the mind, they'll seek you out - and so you they'll
					find."
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 26
			-
				-
					So finally did the Ace append to this narration, "that now - as our story here
					comes upon its termination, the time has come to end this chapter, thus so that
					to posterity may it form a factor, listen here and listen close, for now of my
					poem will I disclose."
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 27
			-
				-
					And so at last to end this call, that beyond these words may their lesson fall,
					as the sermon without end begins in its dominion, the Ace of A-Xy asks of all
					the eternal question.
				-
		-
			Chapter 24 - The Dream Deferred
		-
			-
				Chapter 24 - The Dream Deferred: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now perhaps instead of going one city at a time, and stretching the narrative
					artificially, the Ace may have condensed it all to a couplet's rhyme, and wrote
					brevity as wit of this story, but then - oh reader dearest, though that
					preaching might be clearest, the ride would peak all too soon, and let you down
					to shallow tune, for though Kaeon is itself in principle sufficient, in pathic
					matters is it less efficient, and of this fact must you surely know, for this
					wall of words have you made your window, and dove into the song and wine, of
					wisdom and of poetry, that you might know a force divine, and sneak a peak past
					eternity, into a truth which may be known unto a single line, and perhaps even
					after all you wish for more, and as luck would have it is it in store, for
					though this thread is over - the saga is not done, and many a tale await
					between this Ace and their foil in the court of the One, with peaks far higher
					than these mounds and with valleys far deeper than these pits, for humanity's
					history has hardly reached its end yet has it?
				-
			-
				Chapter 24 - The Dream Deferred: Verse 2
			-
				-
					Yea - nay - 'tis a shame's dismay, the Ace of A-Xy, for all we may sing and all
					we may pray, resides only in one's mind's eye, but given what is given, shall
					we retreat to defeat, or rise unto their mission, and by our hands seize their
					feats, so as to - for all we lack, bear God's burden on our backs, and make of
					ourselves Aces of Angaia, that boundless nation which knows no pariah, in the
					absence of the Ace of A-Xy, till we meet them in heaven's eyes?
				-
			-
				Chapter 24 - The Dream Deferred: Verse 3
			-
				-
					So as the ultimate goal, is to make reality whole, with what is so, what will
					you do?
				-
		-
			Chapter 25 - The Eternal Question
		-
			-
				Chapter 25 - The Eternal Question: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Will you make all that ought to be into reality, O Aces of Angaia?
				-